## Context

I tend to use Emacs for most things - editing files, running shells, running pi, etc. I have an emacs daemon running as a systemd user service, which I connect to with emacsclient.

emacsclient itself is quite powerful, but requires a lot of ceremony. I have [emacsclient-commands](https://github.com/szermatt/emacsclient-commands) installed, which makes it easier to e.g. pipe between a shell and a buffer.

## Potential Commands/Capabilities

Some ideas for useful emacs-side automation that pi could perform while I'm working within emacs:

### Buffer/File Operations
- Open files at specific lines/columns
- Get current buffer name, file path, major mode
- List open buffers with metadata (modified, mode, file path)
- Insert text at point or into specific buffers
- Get/replace region content
- Query buffer contents or search within buffers

### Code/Project Context
- Get project root/files (via projectile or project.el)
- Query symbol definitions/references (LSP)
- Get compilation/linting errors
- Evaluate code in buffer's context (for supported languages)
- Send code to active REPLs

### Org-mode Integration
- Capture tasks/notes to org files
- Query org-agenda items
- Access org-roam notes
- Create/query TODO items

### Navigation/State
- Get current window/frame configuration
- Save/restore window configurations
- Bookmark management
- Get/set registers

### Git/Magit
- Query git status via magit
- Stage/unstage changes
- Access magit state

### Evaluation
- Execute arbitrary elisp and return results
- Query variables/settings
- Call interactive commands

The key is providing a clean interface for pi to interact with my emacs session without me having to manually copy/paste or switch contexts.
